<TITLE> Wellington slam Auckland for using England's Anderson </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 HAMILTON, New Zealand, March 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - New Zealand first class side Wellington have criticised Auckland's signing of England fast bowler James Anderson for their four-day match beginning on Thursday. Anderson, who was not selected for the first test against New Zealand in Hamilton, was released from the England squad to play for Auckland in the domestic competition before rejoining the national team ahead of the second test in Wellington. "We can't get our heads around this," Cricket Wellington chief executive Gavin Larsen told Wellington's Dominion Post newspaper. "It really hits me in the pit of my stomach. "To paint the worst-case scenario, James Anderson takes 7-30 against our boys, Auckland have bowled him into form and before you know it he's opening for England next Thursday here at the Basin (Reserve)." New Zealand Cricket chief executive Justin Vaughan said he was not thrilled about the decision but Auckland were operating within the rules, if somewhat creatively. Auckland's pace bowling stocks have been hit with Kyle Mills and Chris Martin on test duty while Andre Adams and Daryl Tuffey have gone to play in the rebel Indian Cricket League. The four-day match runs until Sunday, with the second test in Wellington beginning on March 13
